Nekrolog der @nytimes:
An earlier version misstated Mr. Wolfe’s age and birth date. He was 88, not 87, and he was born on March 2, 1930, not 1931. The earlier version misstated the title of a novel he published in 2004. It is “I Am Charlotte Simmons,” not “I Am Charlotte Curtis.”

"The Heroin Diaries: A Year in the Life of a Shattered Rock Star" is so brutally honest. If you've EVER been addicted to anything, I highly recommend reading this book.

Is cultural appropriation always racist? No.

author: Shelly Crane
review content: it feels futile, in the midst of something massive, to say "here is my small connection to that thing," like your connection means nothing in the face of Big Cultural Significance, but what is cultural significance if not the sum total of myriad personal connections

author: Shelly Crane
review content: Perhaps the shock of the fire at #NotreDame will help us all reflect on the significance of the #DjapWarrung birthing trees. 800 yrs old, irreplaceable and invaluable in First Nations spiritual and cultural history. Precious, just like ND. Don’t let them go up in smoke too.

author: Shelly Crane
review content: >> @ChrisCuomo now anchoring on @CNN. "We're not used to seeing a historic icon, something of so much significance in this world, no matter what your belief system, literally being destroyed before our eyes."

author: Shelly Crane
review content: Every Wednesday at noon, I would give a tour to English-speaking visitors to Notre Dame. The windows, especially the North Rose Window, are of enormous significance for me. Notre Dame is simply one of the most spiritually charged places in the world. (2/3)

author: Shelly Crane
review content: It's always a tragedy when historic, magnificent, architectural masterpieces are damaged or destroyed, whether they have religious significance or not. #notredamecathedralfire

author: Shelly Crane
review content:
More than just a religious icon, the Notre Dame Cathedral is a cultural, architectural, beautiful work of art of great historical significance. 
So sad to see it up in flames. 
Quelle tristesse.

5 Books on philosophy you have to read:

4 books to avoid: 
Marx -Das Kapital 
Nietzsche - Beyond good and evil
The Bible 
The qur'an

author: Kate Douglas Wiggin
review content: #PrideReads Does a queer book need to have a happy ending? June 25: No! How real would that be? Authors should write their vision of a story’s end, no matter what feeling it evokes. Queer lit. must represent the whole spectrum of emotion, not just Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm!

- Selected Stories ~ Alice Munro. Because no one else writes about us mortals so well.

titles: The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less
author: Barry Schwartz
review content:
Feature request @netflix:

Feeling Lucky:
You have enough data on what I like, but offer me a paralyzing amount of choices. Sometimes I don’t want to think about it so much. 

Required reading for your Product Managers: The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less

titles: The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less
author: Barry Schwartz
review content:

― Barry Schwartz, The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less

titles: The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less
author: Barry Schwartz
review content:
Three great books to read with music in the back of your mind:
—The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less
—Life Inc: How Corporatism Conquered the World, and How We Can Take It Back
—Well-Designed: How to Use Empathy to Create Products People Love

titles: The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less
author: Barry Schwartz
review content: Why More is Less-The paradox of choice. When we have an abundance of options, we are paralyzed in choices. When we have made a choice we seem unfulfilled , wondering if we chose the right one. Left wishing we had made a different choice. Less choice is ironically more satisfying.

titles: The Paradox of Choice: Why More Is Less

titles: From the Corner of His Eye
author: Dean Koontz
review content:
Sentimentality was my undoing. I kept his glass eye as a #memento of the good times. The tricks we played. The fun I had at his expense. 
But I underestimated his powers. For years he’s watched everything from the corner of my office.
The blackmail now is endless.
#vss365

titles: From the Corner of His Eye
author: Dean Koontz
review content:
"I'm melting, Ivanka. Why is it so hot in here?"
Ivanka glided to the thermostat. She read the temperature and pursed her lips.
"Daddy its only 68 degrees."
Trump's neck was covered in sweat. From out of the corner of his eye he saw Mueller's steely visage.
"IT'S SO HOT"

titles: From the Corner of His Eye
author: Dean Koontz
review content:
From the corner of her eye, she traced the waves of his hair from crown to collar where it dusted the fabric of his peacock blue coat. The notes of gold in his brown skin glowed in the lamp light, but what she loved most was the kohl ringing his eyes.
#writeLGBTQ #TheWolfWitch

author: John Irving
review content:
#vss365
I've searched you
Darling belle

Across the face of
Southern skies
Until the sun grew slim
An horizon that lay quiet
Before the gentle night

As if in that hour
The heart
Murmurs no more
But it does
I'd find you yet
Even if Ye be a #pseudonym
You're the one it beats for

review content: On the occasion of his 130th birthday, I think the best Chandler film adaptations rank as follows 1:  The Big Sleep (1946) 2: Murder, My Sweet (1944) 3: The Long Goodbye (1973). I love Artie Wu and the Continental Op, but noir-wise Philip Marlowe is still the private dick for me.

review content: 1962: Silent Spring is an environmental science book, by Rachel Carson, documenting the adverse environmental effects caused by the indiscriminate use of pesticides. Her book spurred a reversal in the United States' national pesticide policy, led to a nationwide ban on DDT for

author: Rachel Carson, Linda Lear, Edward O. Wilson

review content: Hoping to finish @Joannechocolat’s Five Quarters of an Orange today. Third time through and it is just as heart scraping as the first two times. Read it before I had children. Then as a young mom. Now, I reach for more Mirabelle more than Boise. Good ones are worth reading again.

review content: I know Chocolat is the story that most people rave about, but for me Five Quarters of the Orange is my addiction. How many times have I read it? How many times will I read it? Who knows? The point is I love it. @Joannechocolat

 I think: A Prayer for Owen Meany, Bird by Bird, Pride and Prejudice, Five Quarters of the Orange, and poems by Wallace Stevens. I cheated. #top5books

author: Max Lucado
review content:
#Jesus Christ who grew up a carpenter’s Son.  
Worked with wood and nails His whole life. 
Jesus sat in the Garden of Gethsemane knowing full well what He was about to endure.
Yet,
He chose the Cross
He chose the nails
He chose to take our place
HE VOLUNTEERED 
Thank you Lord !

As we enter Holy Week, let us focus 
on Christ, the author and perfecter
Of our faith. Our Savior, who went 
to the cross for you and for me.
He chose the nails that we might
have eternal life if we believe in
Him through faith.

author: Raymond Carver
review content: For centuries, Notre Dame Cathedral has withstood wars, revolutions, and the test of time. It is a symbol of faith & a testament to history. And even as our hearts break to see it burn today during the holiest week of the year for Catholics, I have faith that it will rise again.

author: Raymond Carver
review content: Why has the burning of Notre Dame moved so many? Because we believe in beauty, majesty, faith, art, history, and the human expressions thereof. We recognize in this cathedral our common humanity. A scar now emerges in our connections to our past, our future, and each other.

The block is awkward - it faces west
With long diagonals, sloping too

titles: If You Ask Me (And of Course You Won't)
author: Betty White
review content:
You aren't sure you heard her right. "Excuse me?" You ask, smiling at the nice lady.

She puts one leg over the other and smiles. "I said sit." You of course do as she asked, unable to remember why you wouldn't.

If you don't sit for mistress, she won't call you a good girl.

titles: If You Ask Me (And of Course You Won't)
author: Betty White
review content:
#BettyWhite #WednesdayWisdom 

“Why do people say “grow some balls”? Balls are weak and sensitive. If you wanna be tough, grow a vagina. Those things can take a pounding.” — From her book, If You Ask Me (And Of Course You Won’t)

titles: If You Ask Me (And of Course You Won't)
author: Betty White
review content: When i don't like you, i won't try to talk to you or anything BUT if you ask for my help, of course i'll help you. I don't understand WHY do people expect me to be mean to people i hate?? There's a difference to being a fucking DECENT human being and being FAKE.

titles: If You Ask Me (And of Course You Won't)
author: Betty White
review content: All my life I obey you. Since you insist ,thats for my own sake, you didn't even listen to my side. Now can I ask you a favor?  Can you please let me decide for myself, Just once?  If I fail well of course I can learn from it and I'll make sure it won't happen again.

titles: If You Ask Me (And of Course You Won't)
author: Betty White
review content:
When friends are about to tell me something and they ask me to promise them not to tell anyone-- of course I won't. I'll probably forget everyhing you said a few minutes after telling me so your secret is definitely safe. 

Not sure if that's good or bad but it's safe.

titles: If You Ask Me (And of Course You Won't)

author: James Surowiecki
review content:
The wisdom of crowds.
https://www.express.co.uk/news/politics/1053817/brexit-news-theresa-may-brexit-deal-jacob-rees-mogg …

author: James Surowiecki
review content: Remember when “the wisdom of crowds” was a thing? well LOL Twitter sure disabused us of that notion.

author: James Surowiecki
review content:
Today, @GavinVerhey asked people to name their all-time favorite Limited commons. As I am such a good helper, I thought I could use the wisdom of crowds to help him out.

What’s the most fun Limited common of all-time?

author: James Surowiecki
review content: BeTtInG mArKeTs AgGrEgAtE iNfOrMaTiOn FrOm ThoSaNdS oF wEiRd PeOpLe aCcRoSs EuRoPe WhO pUt SmAlL aMoUnTs Of MoNeY oN tHe LiNe BeTtInG oN tHe OuTcOmE oF aMeRiCaN pOlItIcAl EvEnTs. HaRd To SeE hOw YoU bEaT tHe WiSdOm Of CrOwDs.

author: James Surowiecki
review content:
When people reference the "wisdom of crowds", they generally mean something more like: "the statistical aggregate of otherwise diffuse individual behaviors, acting context-specifically."

That is not a crowd.

A embodied crowd is seldom wiser than a paramecium.

Often less so.

author: James Surowiecki
review content:
the more you do this the more you realize that appealing to “industry consensus” has little value outside of the generic wisdom of crowds

there are industry people whose opinions have great value, far more than my own, but they’re not usually the ones reflected in said consensus

author: James Surowiecki
review content: On social media and the wisdom of crowds. pic.twitter.com/wNdjzNhL2R

author: James Surowiecki
review content: Congest pricing: The wisdom of crowds has prevailed! Those crowds, the millions of NYrs suffering with poor transit, slow speeds.I congratulate Speaker Heastie Leader Stewart Cousins and especially Gov Cuomo. The Gov knew a World City can’t thrive with a crumbling transit system.

author: James Surowiecki
review content:
Pundits have no idea what will happen next, so let's test the wisdom of crowds..

Q: Unless backbench Labour MPs bail-out May by voting for current Withdrawal Agreement (unlikely, I hope) she has four options. Which do you think is most likely? 

(note - not which do you prefer!)

author: James Surowiecki
review content: Can we use the wisdom of crowds to correctly nail tomorrow's Brexit vote? Please vote what you think will happen, not what you'd like to see happen. Tomorrow night we can assess how well we all did collectively!

author: Chris Bohjalian
review content: In Bury St Edmunds it's sobering to remember what was lost. The Benedictine Abbey, destroyed at the Dissolution, was one of England's finest buildings. The ruins, visible in Abbey gardens, are still impressive. Heartbreaking though, in the light of current events. #NotreDamepic.twitter.com/rJccXNdhgn – at St Edmundsbury Cathedral

author: Chris Bohjalian
review content:
"See the light of the afterworld shining on the ruins
It's the light of nowhere else burning to the west
See its sulphury shine
See the big city moon
Tween the radio towers
Tween the big diesel rigs
In the Midwest's witching hour
I watch the whole town eclipse"

author: Chris Bohjalian
review content:
You rescued me
from the ruins
where the forsaken 
lay buried

The light
in your soul
found me gasping
for compassion
among a world
of stone

I learned to breathe
on the air of your voice
as you guided me home
with trust
that never faltered
#Poetry

review content:
Making the decision to speak up has cost me everything.

My happily ever after to a man I was in love with.
My beloved dog Frank.
My ability to find gainful employment. 
My freedom to move through this world as I had always had.
It left me broke and nearly homeless.

author: Michel Houellebecq, Frank Wynne
review content:
Quarks are elementary particles that build up the protons and neutrons inside an atom. There are currently six known quarks:

- Up
- Down
- Charm
- Strangeness
- Top
- Bottom

#physics #quarks #particles #science #atoms #matter

author: Michel Houellebecq, Frank Wynne
review content:
A Higgs boson walks into a Catholic church and the priest says “I’m sorry, we don’t allow elementary particles in this church” 

“Excuse me!” Says the Higgs boson “without me, you can’t have mass!”

author: Michel Houellebecq, Frank Wynne
review content: Neutrinos remain the most interesting elementary particles in nature, at least for me, and perhaps also the most likely to provide some experimental direction in the search for new fundamental physics beyond the Standard Model.  https://physics.aps.org/articles/v11/30?utm_campaign=weekly&utm_medium=email&utm_source=emailalert …

“Language: The Cultural Tool,” @amazonrambler

review content:
The cultural gap in this country is not only big and fundamental, it's also expanding, like the universe.

And like the expanding universe, there will come a day where everything will blow up and disintegrate into unbound elementary particles.

This country is doomed.

author: Michel Houellebecq, Frank Wynne
review content: Here's a real fact instead: The ball-model of elementary particles was abandoned about a century ago. There is nothing empty about a space filled with quantum fields.

author: Michel Houellebecq, Frank Wynne
review content:
2008 Physics Laureate Yoichiro Nambu was born on 18 January 1921 in Tokyo, Japan. 

In 1960, Yoichiro Nambu formulated a mathematical theory for understanding symmetry violations, giving a basis for better understanding the elementary particles and their interactions. pic.twitter.com/EBC9AISu9t

author: Georgia Cates
Georgia Cates
review content: There is a strong potential for feeling overwhelmed from this mass amount of energy coming in. Surrender to the Flow. It's a good night to take a bath, light some candles, and enjoy the beauty of your own Spirit. All is well.

author: Georgia Cates
review content: The beauty in pain and suffering reveals itself when you begin to surrender and lean not on your own understanding. God doesn’t just blow the wind in your direction without reason. He wants you to learn from the cold so you can make the most of the sun when it shines.

author: Georgia Cates
review content: What a nice surprise, while nipping into the local @Waterstones just now, to hear them playing 'Sweet Surrender' from @laurenhousley's terrific album 'The Beauty Of This Life'. Things are looking up! pic.twitter.com/YEjqBkqbXC

author: Georgia Cates
review content:
“A glance from him drives men to their knees
His sigh brings cities to ruin
I wonder if he dreams of surrender
On a bed of white flowers
Or is that the mistaken hope
Of every would-be conqueror?
The world was not made for beauty like his”

author: Georgia Cates
review content: Surrender all the broken pieces to Jesus and you will see how He will make beauty from the broken

author: Georgia Cates
review content: The beauty lies in the brute stupidity of a primitive species, with a capacity to surrender to the infinite and merge. Art stems from there.

author: Georgia Cates
review content: "I stare out of a window. A large oak returns my gaze. The gentle wind blows me from side to side, like a protective mother rocking her demon child. Countyside camouflage has no expectation, no beauty, no surrender."-The invisible country, @youngsunghero on Zathom

author: Georgia Cates
review content: The beauty of our recovery programme. It’s so powerful. My soul was at it’s lowest ebb last year. Never felt so much emotional & spiritual pain. Moved on miles from then. Pain has been my best teacher. Point being, I suffered with my ego today.  Had to surrender it to get peace

author: Georgia Cates
review content: Even if you feel your heart is breaking, find peace and comfort in surrender, you find Him there, restoring, reshaping, and creating beauty from the ashes, from the very thing you thought would take you down. HE IS STRENGTHENING AND MAKES ALL THINGS NEW! Surrender, He is here.

author: Georgia Cates
review content:
Life is The Universe’s attempt to hide from entropy

I’m thinking sometimes it’s helpful to just surrender and revel in its formidable beauty

Dreams, man.

author: James M. McPherson
review content: In 1862, musician & composer George Root wrote the song "The Battle Cry of Freedom." It became an instant hit in the North, so much so that there were reports of US troops singing it in battle. The chorus contains a key word that depicted how most US troops viewed Confederates: pic.twitter.com/jWn2HFAzLi

author: James M. McPherson
review content: Listening to Battle Cry of Freedom makes me sadder+more angry about the paucity of monuments to black heroes in the former confederacy. To quote Rabbi Hillel, black men+women who fought to save the Union are more deserving of monuments than the white men who fought to destroy it.

review content: The double bind of presenting on Jewish topics while female: If I use Hebrew words, I risk being seen as elitist and therefore too out of touch to be worth listening to. If I substitute English words, I risk being seen as ignorant and too inauthentic to be worth listening to.

author: Chris Bohjalian
review content:
The double bind every policy advocacy group faces right now:

1) In order to pass legislation, you have to work with both parties. 

2) The GOP is actively threatening democracy, and anything that strengthens their perceived legitimacy is dangerous. 

What do you do with that?

review content:
It should also be pointed out this dynamic systemically hurts female candidates. 

If a woman ran on vague platitudes she’d be criticized for not being specific. 

Then when she does offer specifics she’s criticized for not being inspiring. 

The double bind at work.

titles: The Edge of Always (The Edge of Never, #2)
author: J.A. Redmerski
review content:
My mans was standing on the edge of the bathtub dancing and he goes “imagine if you had a normal boyfriend who never did stuff like this!”
In my head I was like ‘I’ve had that. I got bored.’ 
This is why I love Aquarius energy. I’m always entertained.

titles: The Edge of Always (The Edge of Never, #2)

review content: Well as always when I watch a Hospital Programme Surgeons: At the Edge of Life BBC2, I'm absolutely amazed, admire and respect these wonderful People and what they do to save Peoples lives. It never ceases to amaze me of their Passion, dedication and fantastic compassion.

titles: The Edge of Always (The Edge of Never, #2)
author: J.A. Redmerski
review content:
Devastated that one of my beautiful twitter friends tried to take their own life but so thankful they have pulled through  
You never know what could tip someone over the edge. Be kind always! 
Mental illness is a fucker and sometimes it gets too much. 
But kindness helps

titles: The Edge of Always (The Edge of Never, #2)

She always dreamt of stranger worlds
Standing on the edge as the view unfurled

Different from the masses swirling around
Never able to bring her down
Those who saw her inner light

The Edge, right before climax:
Don't think about that moment lasting until the end of time.  Don't think about that moment stretching out into eternity. Don't think about that moment. Never. Ending.  About always wanting. Never fulfilled. Just needing. Forever. And forever.

titles: Salt Sugar Fat: How the Food Giants Hooked Us
author: Michael Moss
review content:
Sounds good. The title reminds me of a different book, Salt Sugar Fat: How the Food Giants Hooked Us, about the history of processed food.

My takeaways: Some foods need salt & fat for taste, people can adapt to eat more or less sugar, there are no good low-fat dairy cheeses.

Fight for your happiness. And don't quit on your dreams.

author: Charles M. Sheldon
review content:
"Gale..."

A smile he knew by every crevice. The grace in his steps, the tone of his voice. 
How could he know it would end like this?

Lies. Everything was lies.

He stares at the dark of the moonlit sky. 

Even after all this time, the burn of tears is fresh on his cheeks.

author: Charles M. Sheldon
review content:
Another shake of his head.

His expression was quite sad. It would make one want to console him.

❝...No.❞

However, he follows after his Shizun with a light bounce in his steps. He inwardly cheers as he walks into the chambers.

author: J.D. Robb
review content:
Today made me had a different impression about friendship and I promise to do better.

I watched my brother’s friends lay down his coffin today, I saw them struggle like their life depended on it.

Even in death, his friends were protective of him. 

Who are you to your friends?

review content: Rather than the coldness of his armor, the warmth of his skin had always been a blessing. Leaning against his touch, Igrane spoke softly. "Neither in life nor in death will we be parted, I promise you this." Her expression becomes doleful,"I could not bare to lose you as well."

the greatest pretender

author: N.K. Jemisin
review content: The Broken Earth Trilogy? Hype it up. Two of the protagonists are black. One isn't human, but is a black-marbled talking rock. I figure that counts. Individual books do NOT stand alone. THE FIFTH SEASON, THE OBELISK GATE, and THE STONE SKY are their names. No omnibus.

author: N.K. Jemisin
review content:
So, the Broken Earth trilogy is currently cheaper as a set than by buying each book individually at Amazon. FYI.

In other news, I just finished The Fifth Season and will shortly have two copies of it. I'll probably give the new one to my niece for Christmas.

Dad: hey, what's your name?

review content: To find beauty in what is left behind is not to condone the taking, the desecration. I stood here today buffeted by the unusually warm winds of February and thought about the machines that chewed, that mauled, that took, that forever changed these hills. Any recs?

author: Robert Kurson
review content:
Just read Shadow Divers. Great book! Takeaways:

1) Much of history is wrong. Reminds me of @AmuseChimp’s line: “if the news is fake, imagine history.”

2) Be the best in the world at something and luck finds you.

3) Shipwreck diving is freakin intense. Respect to the committed.

Once upon a time I had this beautiful girl in my life who made me really happy, and I lost her because I'm dumb. The end.

author: David Foster Wallace
review content:
Seems pretty easy to make an argument that DFW’s impetus for Brief Interviews with Hideous Men is working A.A. steps 4 & 5:

4. Made a searching and fearless moral inventory of ourselves.
5. Admitted to God, to ourselves, and to another human being the exact nature of our wrongs.

review content: What novel do you wish you could go back and read and experience for the first time? Tonight I'm thinking of A Sheltering Sky by Paul Bowles

author: Paul Bowles
review content: ”We get to think of life as an inexhaustible well. Yet everything happens a certain number of times, and a very small number, really. How many more times will you watch the full moon rise? Perhaps twenty. And yet it all seems limitless.” - The Sheltering Sky

author: Paul Bowles
review content:
When a parent dies, for those left behind it can feel as though half of the sky has fallen. My father was the sheltering sky, and beneath his mild firmament no storm ever raged, no hard rain fell, writes John Birmingham

author: Paul Bowles
review content:
These lines from Paul Bowles' The Sheltering Sky are forever etched into my mind.

"Death is always on the way, but the fact that you don't know when it will arrive seems to take away from the finiteness of life. It's that terrible precision that we hate so much. (1/3)

author: Paul Bowles
review content: How fragile we are under the sheltering sky. Behind the sheltering sky is a vast dark universe, and we're just so small.
